{[%evp 0,26,22,22,70,66,43,27,62,30,38,12,7,2,2,-1,5,-4,-2,-5,-3,0,-12,-5,3,-9,
0,15,22]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e5 {Relatively rare continuation even
though we can find over 1000 games in online Database, certainly much more
popular are the well-known moves such as 3...g6, 3...e6, 3...d6 or even 3...
Nf6.} 4. Bxc6 ({Overall pretty harmless} 4. Nc3 d6 {I believe White's
light-squared bishop would be better placed on c4 and therefore 3.Nc3 e5 4.Bc4
is more challenging.} 5. d3 (5. O-O Nf6 6. d3 {see through 5. d3 move order})
5... Nf6 6. Bg5 {[%csl Gd8,Gf6]} ({Another line is} 6. O-O Be7 7. Bg5 {
important to mention} (7. Nd5 {it appears that Black can even play here} Nxd5
$1 {Of course Black is also fine after} (7... O-O {I even found my old game} 8.
Nxe7+ Nxe7 9. Bg5 {[%csl Gf6]} Ng6 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 10. Nh4 Nf4 $5 11. Bc4 h6 {
[%csl Gg5]} 12. Bxf4 exf4 {with balanced play Galego,L-Avrukh,B Burguillos 2007
}) 8. exd5 {[%csl Gc6]} a6 {[%csl Gb5] an obvious point of Black's idea} 9. Ba4
b5 {[%csl Ga4]} 10. dxc6 bxa4 11. c3 {Evseev,N-Volynets, V Soviet Union 1972
Now it looks like after the most accurate} Qa5 $146 12. Re1 Qb5 $1 {[%csl Gc6]}
13. d4 Qxc6 14. dxe5 d5 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7] Black's chances seem to me
preferable thanks to his bishop pair.}) 7... O-O 8. Bc4 {Basically White is
tempo down to compare with 3.Nc3 e5 4.Bc4 line.} (8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nd5 {see 6.
Bg5}) 8... Nd7 {[%csl Gg5]} (8... Ne8 $5 {seems like a good move as well}) 9.
Bxe7 Nxe7 {[%csl Gd5]} 10. a4 Nf6 11. Re1 {Hamann,H-Isigkeit,H GER email 2012
and now I would suggest} a6 $146 {[%csl Gb5]} 12. h3 {White cannot play} (12.
a5 {in view of} Nc6 {[%csl Ga5]}) 12... h6 $15 {with a very comfortable
position for Black.}) 6... Be7 {since 7.0-0 would transpose to 6.0-0 line, I
will examine two other options} 7. Bxf6 (7. a3 O-O 8. Bc4 {Perez Ponsa,F-Perez
Gormaz,M Buenos Aires 2015 a very good idea for Black here is} ({I would like
to mention the following game} 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nd2 $6 Bg5 10. O-O g6 11. Nd5 {
this happened in Al Sayed,M-Demchenko,A St Petersburg 2018 A nice improvement
over the game would be} a6 $146 12. Bc4 b5 {[%csl Gc4]} 13. Ba2 Kh8 {[%cal
Gf7f5] and Black has a dream position.}) 8... Nd7 $1 $146 9. Bxe7 {in case of}
(9. Be3 Nb6 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5]} 10. Ba2 Be6 $15 {Black is already slightly better.
}) 9... Nxe7 {[%csl Gd5]} 10. h3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] no problems for Black
whatsoever.}) 7... Bxf6 8. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5]} O-O 9. O-O Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5]} 10.
Bc4 {[%csl Gd5] hardly a good idea for White} (10. c4 $6 {[%csl Gd4]
Remizov-Buksa, Lichess. org INT 2021 Black could immediately take advantage by
means of} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nd4 13. Qd1 g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,
Gf7f5] Black has a better game.}) 10... g6 {[%cal Gf6g7]} 11. c3 Bg7 12. a3 {
[%cal Gb2b4] All this happened in Caruana, F-Carlsen,M Moscow 2013 I would
suggest here a new idea} Rb8 $146 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 13. b4 b5 14. Bb3 a5 $132 {
[%csl Gb4] with double-edged play.}) 4... dxc6 5. d3 {[%csl Ge5] Obviously
capturing e5-pawn is hardly a good idea for White} (5. Nxe5 $6 Qd4 $1 {[%csl
Ge4,Ge5]} 6. Nf3 Qxe4+ 7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 {Three games arrived to this
position. Black got great positions in all three games, however I believe the
most precise would be} Nf6 $146 9. Re1 Nd5 10. Kf1+ {[%csl Ge8]} Be7 11. d3 f6
{[%csl Gc8,Ge7][%cal Ge8f7] Black has better endgame thanks to his bishop pair}
) (5. O-O {[%csl Ge5]} f6 {[%csl Ge5]} (5... Bd6 {good move as well}) 6. d3 ({
Doesn't work} 6. Nxe5 $2 fxe5 7. Qh5+ {[%csl Ge5,Ge8]} Kd7 $1 8. Qxe5 Qf6 $1
$17 {White has no sufficient compensation for the sacrificed material Mohota,
N-Kornyukov,A Chess.com INT 2020}) 6... Ne7 7. a4 {this happened in Bryan,
J-Suarez Uriel,A Chess.com 2021. Here I would suggest} ({Another game featured
} 7. Be3 {[%csl Gc5]} Ng6 {[%cal Gf8c5]} 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. h3 O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 $15 {
Black obtained pleasant edge in Spanton, T-Bhend,E Triesen 2005}) 7... Ng6 $146
8. a5 Be6 9. Be3 Be7 10. Nbd2 Qd7 $11 {[%csl Ge6,Ge7] with a comfortable
position for Black.}) 5... Bd6 6. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] Two other options:} (6. h3
{[%csl Gg4]} Ne7 7. Nc3 ({or} 7. a4 O-O 8. Na3 ({Another game here followed} 8.
a5 f6 {[%csl Ge5]} 9. Nbd2 Be6 {[%csl Gc4]} 10. Nc4 {[%csl Gd6]} Bc7 {[%csl
Ga5] Black had no problems whatsoever Muller-Nandhidhaa, Europe Echecs INT 2021
}) 8... Bc7 {another good move} (8... Ng6) 9. Be3 {[%csl Gc5]} b6 10. O-O a5 $1
{preventing a4-a5 move} 11. Qd2 Ng6 {Black got better game in Fischer,J-Dardha,
D Europe Echecs INT 2021}) 7... Ng6 {[%csl Ge5]} 8. O-O {Cajbel,M-Kosiorek,M
Warsaw 2013 after the natural} f6 $146 9. Be3 Be6 $15 {[%csl Gd6,Ge6] Black
has a very nice position with a bishop pair.}) (6. Be3 Nf6 7. h3 {in both
games where this position happened Black prefered 7...c4, I would rather keep
the existing pawn structure and just continue} Qe7 $146 8. Nbd2 Bc7 $15 {
and Black is comfortable with bishop pair.}) 6... f6 {Strenghtening the
e5-pawn and by doing this Black avoids giving up his bishop pair in case of
Nc4.} 7. Nc4 Bc7 {[%csl Gc7,Gc8]} 8. Be3 {[%csl Gc5]} b6 {[%csl Gc5]} 9. a3 {
[%cal Gb2b4] A critical try} ({Another game saw} 9. O-O {Vulevic, V-Podlesnik,
B Herceg Novi 2020 Now, the simple} Ne7 $146 10. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5]} a5 $15 {
would have led to a better position for Black.}) {this position occurred in
the game Gvetadze, S-Javakhishvili, L Tbilisi 2016 Here I would suggest} 9...
Ne7 $146 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 O-O 12. O-O Ng6 13. Ra3 f5 $132 {and Black
starts counterplay on the kingside.} *

