-30,-30,-32,-23]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {This move together with
Rossolimo (3.Bb5) are two important variations, which has to be studied for
Black players' options for 2... Nc6. Especially, it might give a lot of
headache to Sveshnikov and Kalashnikov players. Many years ago, when I started
to play Sveshnikov, the move 3.Nc3 was one of the reasons I eventually gave up
on 2... Nc6. Definitely, I would seriously consider this opening again after
all Magnus games and explosion of new ideas for Black.} e5 {This is my choice.
What I like about this specific choice is that this line is independent,
meaning it can be played by not only players, who want to play Sveshnikov, or
Kalashnikov systems, but also by those, who intend to play other Sicilian
variations, whether it's Taimanov, Accelerated Dragon, or Richter-Rauzer.
Another important reason, it's the same pawn structure as well as in our
Rossolimo variation 3...e5, so it's a good fit for our concept.} 4. d3 ({
First of all} 4. Bb5 {transpose to Rossolimo variation}) (4. g3 g6 {Black can
also choose finachetto} 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d3 d6 7. O-O ({Quite often in this type
of closed pawn structure we can see the following idea} 7. h4 {Black can
