of consideration}) 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $11 {and Black comfortably equalized in
Inarkiev,E-Roiz,M Moscow 2003}) 10... Qxe7 11. Bb5 {Hild, H-Eschert,U ICCF
email 2019. Now, Black should have simply played} (11. Ne3 Be6 12. b3 {covered
through 10.Nfe3 line}) 11... O-O $146 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Ng3 Bd7 $13 {[%cal
Gf7f5] Black is ready for f5-advance and has comfortable game.}) 9... Bg5 {
[%csl Gd2]} 10. O-O Be6 11. Qd1 {getting away from the pin} O-O 12. Ned5 {
White also tried} (12. a4 Nb6 13. Ba2 ({Another game featured} 13. Bxe6 fxe6
14. a5 Nd7 $15 {and I prefer Black position Oger,C-Datler,W ICCF email 2013})
13... Bxa2 14. Rxa2 Nc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8e7] Black's knight is heading to e7,
where it will help to prepare f7-f5 advance and to help with the fight over
d5-square.} 15. Ra1 N8e7 16. Ncd5 Nxd5 ({There is nothing wrong with} 16...
Bxe3 $5 17. fxe3 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 17. Nxd5 Bxc1 18. Rxc1 Ne7 $11 {
and Black equalized in Bucek-Hybl,V ICCF email 2010}) 12... Bxc1 13. Qxc1 Nd4 {
[%cal Gf7f5]} 14. a4 f5 $1 {and Black has no problems whatsoever Kilichenko,
A-Pecka, J ICCF email 2015}) 8... Be6 9. Ne3 {[%csl Gd5]} O-O 10. O-O {It's
hard to believe White can benefit from delaying immediate castle, one example}
(10. a3 Nh5 {[%cal Ge7g5]} 11. Ncd5 Bg5 12. O-O Ne7 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} 13. Nxe7+
Qxe7 14. a4 {[%csl Gb5]} Rad8 15. Qe1 h6 $11 {with balanced play in Staroske,
U-Martin Sanchez,C ICCF email 2020}) 10... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] It wouldn't
surprise that Black can equalise with alternative move, however the text looks
very logical to me} 11. a4 {[%csl Gb5]} ({Of course, there are alternative
moves} 11. Bd5 {[%csl Gc6]} Qd7 12. a4 {[%csl Gb5]} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} 13. a5
{two games arrived to this position. Now I believe Black should have played}
Rae8 14. Kh1 Bd8 {with very complex battle.}) (11. a3 b5 {[%csl Gc4]} 12. Ba2
Bxa2 13. Rxa2 Qd7 {[%cal Ge7d8]} 14. Ra1 {Another game here featured} (14. Kh1
{Dessaules,P-Ametrano,A ICCF email 2021. Here, I would suggested the following
improvement} Rae8 {[%cal Ge7d8]} 15. Bd2 {in case of} (15. Nf5 {Black can
easily play} d5 $1) 15... Bd8 16. Be1 Nh5 {[%cal Gd8g5,Gg7g6] with complex but
pretty balanced play.}) 14... Rae8 15. Ng4 $5 {Tarlev,K-Deac,B Calimanesti
Caciulata 2016 now I like the following improvement} ({In case of} 15. f4 {
Black can react with} exf4 16. Rxf4 Bd8 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 15... Bd8 $1 {[%cal
Gf6h5]} 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Nd5 {[%csl Gf6]} Bd8 18. c3 Ne7 $11 {with equality.}
) 11... Rb8 {Keeping in mind the b7-b5 advance} 12. Bd2 {two other popular
continuations} (12. Rf2 Nb4 {taking advantage of a2-a4-move} 13. a5 {now Black
is well set for} d5 $1 14. exd5 Nfxd5 15. Nexd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 {doesn't change
much} (16. Bd2 Re8 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. b3 f5 {Robson,N-Bubir,S
ICCF email 2018}) 16... Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Qxd5 18. b3 {[%csl Gc4]} f5 19. Bb2 Rbe8
20. Re2 {[%csl Ge5]} Bf6 {[%csl Ge5]} 21. Ra4 Re6 $1 22. Rc4 Be7 23. Qe1 Bd6
$11 {Gnutov,Y-Kloster,S ICCF email 2019}) (12. Ned5 Nb4 {[%csl Gd5] fighting
for d5-square} 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Bg5 {This move is definitely critical. The
examplary line here is} h6 15. Bh4 g5 {[%csl Gh4]} 16. Bf2 Nh5 17. a5 Nf4 {
[%cal Gf7f5] with an active position for Black in Koval,V-Oomen,A ICCF email
2018}) 12... Nh5 {Starting counterplay on the kingisde} 13. g3 {White also
tried} (13. Ncd5 {this allows} b5 {[%csl Gc4]} 14. axb5 axb5 15. Bb3 Bg5 {
[%csl Ge3]} 16. g3 {[%cal Gf3f4]} Bxe3+ $1 17. Bxe3 Nd4 {[%csl Gb3]} 18. Ba2
Ra8 $11 {with balanced play Poli,G-Schramm,A ICCF email 2017}) 13... Bg5 {
[%csl Ge3]} 14. Ng2 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 {this occured in Movsesian,S-Moiseenko,A
Germany 2021 now I would suggest the following improvement} Bh3 $146 16. Rf2
