{[%evp 0,48,30,42,42,40,40,32,32,39,39,38,67,32,32,32,32,27,27,27,30,28,36,23,
32,15,23,4,19,12,7,-2,7,-10,14,14,14,7,7,2,6,-5,22,28,-8,-26,-35,-35,-21,-21,
-11]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. O-O Nf6 7. Bg5 O-O
8. Bxf6 (8. h3 {you can find in 6.h3 variation}) 8... Bxf6 9. Nd5 {very
important line for understanding of this variation. At first glance it looks
like White can claim positional advantage thanks to his full control over
d5-square. However, it appears that thanks to good control over the center
mainly due to e5 and c5 pawns Black can safely move to preparing thematic
f7-f5 advance, without even fighting for d5-square.} g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gg8h8,
Gf7f5] Black is planning Bg7, Kh8, f5.} 10. c3 ({This is the last opportunity
for White to capture on f6} 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. h3 {[%csl Gg4]} Be6 12. c3 (12.
Nh2 {[%cal Gh2g4]} h5 {[%csl Gg4]} 13. Qd2 {Shytaj,L-Carron,J Lausanne 2003 in
my opinion natural} Rad8 $146 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 15. f4 exf4 16. Qxf4
d5 $13 {would easily solve problems for Black.}) 12... Rad8 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 13.
Bxe6 {this happeened in Yu,Y-Moiseenko, A Dubai 2014 Black should have
recaptured by means of} Qxe6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 14. Re1 d5 15. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7]} b6
{with equal game.}) 10... Bg7 {in my opinion the critical line is} 11. a4 Kh8
12. Qd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] premature} (12. b4 cxb4 13. Nxb4 {or} (13. cxb4 Bg4 {
[%csl Gd4] and Black gets control over d4-square}) 13... f5 $1 14. Nd5 Na5 {
Black was already better in Eric,J-Savina,A Kemer 2009}) 12... Bd7 {another
reliable option for Black} (12... Rb8 13. b4 $5 {this happened in Agrawal,
R-Prakash,O ICCF email 2015 here I would suggest the following improvement}
cxb4 14. cxb4 Bg4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3]} 15. Ne1 Qh4 {[%cal Gg7h6]} 16. Nc2 Bh6 $1
17. Qe1 b6 $11 {with complicated game.}) 13. b4 f5 14. exf5 {other options:} (
14. bxc5 dxc5 15. Qe3 {Goncharenko,G-Churkin,M ICCF email 2015 now Black can
play} Na5 $146 {[%csl Gc4]} 16. Nd2 b6 $13 {with double-edged play.}) (14. b5
Na5 {[%csl Gc4]} 15. Ba2 {now Black has the folllowing idea} fxe4 16. dxe4 Rxf3
$1 17. gxf3 Bh3 18. Kh1 {Cirulis,I-Seiler, P LSS email 2020 after natural} Bxf1
19. Rxf1 Qh4 $13 {[%cal Gg7h6] the play is more or less balanced, although
position remains very complicated.}) 14... gxf5 15. b5 Ne7 {worth considering}
(15... Na5 $5 16. Ba2 Rc8 {[%cal Gc5c4]}) 16. Qg5 $1 {White has to simplify in
order to avoid running under Black attack} Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Bf6 {[%csl Gg5]} 18.
Qh6 Rb8 {[%csl Gb7]} 19. Rae1 Qe7 20. c4 f4 21. Nd2 Rg8 $1 22. Qh5 ({Black
rook was untouchable , since after} 22. Bxg8 $2 Rxg8 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gg8g6]
and White queen is trapped}) 22... Rg6 23. Qe2 Qg7 24. Kh1 Rh6 $13 {and it
looks dangerous for White Morrow,W-Gerola,G ICCF email 2021} *

