complex play.}) 17... Rae8 18. f4 Bxa2 19. Rxa2 h6 $1 20. Bxf6 ({White cannot
play} 20. Bh4 $2 {in view of} Nxe4 {[%csl Gh4]}) 20... Bxf6 21. Nd5 Bd4 {
[%csl Gg1]} 22. Re1 f5 $1 23. c3 Bf6 24. Raa1 Bh4 25. Re3 c4 $15 {[%csl Gd3,
Ge4] and Black seized the initiaitve in Bubnov,V-Koch,C LSS email 2018}) 10...
b5 {[%csl Gc4]} 11. Ba2 exf4 12. Qxf4 Qd7 13. Qf2 Rae8 14. h3 Be6 $1 15. Be3 {
This position happened in Beckett, P-Skryago, M ICCF email 2016 Black should
have played} ({Black would be happy to accept the following pawn structure} 15.
Nxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Gf2,Gf8]} 16. Qe1 d5 $1 $17) 15... Bxa2 $146 16. Rxa2 Ne5 $15
{[%cal Gd6d5] with very comfortable position for Black.}) 9... b5 {[%csl Gc4]}
10. Bd5 ({In case of} 10. Bb3 {Black responds with} Nd4 {targeting White
light-squared bishop.}) 10... Bd7 {[%cal Gf6d5]} ({It took me some time to
understand what happens after} 10... Nxd5 {[%cal Ge7g5] it's appears that
White has} 11. Nxh7 $1 {It appears White initiatve is enough to maintain the
balance, for example} (11. exd5 $2 Nd4 {[%csl Gf5,Gg5] White cannot avoid
losing material.}) 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Kxh7 13. Qh5+ {[%csl Gh7]} Kg8 14. Rf3 {
[%cal Gf3h3]} Bh4 15. Rh3 Ra7 16. Rxh4 f6 {it looks like Black is safe with
extra piece, however here comes White's second wave of attack} 17. g4 $1 Qe8 {
[%csl Gh5]} 18. Qh7+ Kf7 19. g5 Rg8 {[%csl Gg7]} 20. Rg4 fxg5 21. Bxg5 Kf8 {
here I examined the following line} 22. Bh4 {[%cal Gg4g6]} Qf7 23. Rg6 {
[%csl Gd6]} Ke8 24. Rxd6 g6 {[%csl Gh7]} 25. Qxf7+ Rxf7 26. Rxc6 gxf5+ {
[%csl Gg1]} 27. Kh1 Kd7 28. Rh6 Bb7 $11) 11. Nxh7 $1 {otherwise White is worse}
Nxh7 12. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3h3]} Bg5 13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Rg3 Qh4 15. Rh3 Qg5 16. Rg3 {
